I often think that the Millennials may be the last generation able to genuinely appreciate art and form genuine connections with artists. They don't face that pressure to view everything through a critical, biased lens.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, but now this collective consciousness has disappeared.
At that time, we could immerse ourselves directly in the content without needing to consider its source, because in those days, tracing back its origins was not easy.
We revered these artists as if they were gods, and there was no reason to question this worship. Thus, we formed a "pseudo-social relationship" with them, and regarded it as an essential part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
While the show "The Office" was still airing, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together, eating pizza and catching up on the episodes.
This is quite different from our current experience of watching shows through streaming platforms. Streaming services usually release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches at their own pace. When posting about the plot on social media, we often add "spoiler warning," or simply discuss in specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all long for that sense of collective belonging that once connected everyone.
It's precisely because of this nostalgia that we keep rewatching TV shows like "The Office" or movies like "The King of Comedy," whose iconic lines spread like memes online and become widely recognized.
We quote these classic lines from the works and assume most people understand what we're referring to.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we cannot assume that everyone has seen it.
With the explosion of information, there is simply too much to pay attention to, and it's impossible to filter it all... Are we ever going to be able to escape this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find out that they are either sexual predators with a history of misconduct or stubborn individuals filled with prejudice, and this cycle is exhausting.
We are caught between nostalgia and the realization that the people who created the art we love may have serious moral flaws, and this conflicting mindset leaves us feeling confused and unsure.
We will be more cautious in forming "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realized that it is difficult to ensure one does not harm or exploit others if they wish to gain wealth and power.
Since the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are still some people who are stubbornly misguided, insisting on idolizing others, and then pretending to be shocked when the idol falls.
We are in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
